  "body": "There is a bug in `TypeUtils.isNullableType` and its IrType analogue `IrType.isNullable`.\r\n\r\nBoth functions are supposed to check that a given type is not a subtype of `Any`. For type parameters the implementation checks whether there is *any* nullable upper bound. This is the wrong way around --- when we have  a type parameter with multiple upper bounds such as `T : Any, T : I?` both\r\nfunctions return true, even though `T` is declared to be a subtype of `Any`.\r\n\r\nSimilarly `IrType.makeNotNull` does not work at all in the case of type parameters.\r\n\r\nThis PR fixes both problems.\r\n\r\nSince type parameters with mutliple upper bounds are rare, neither bug causes any test failures whatsoever. I have added a test case where the bug will lead to a missing parameter null-check and a test for another situation involving recursive upper bounds.\r\n\r\nSince `IrType.makeNotNull` is declared in ir.tree I had to move WrappedDescriptors and `IrType.isNullable` to this package. This implies that we need a corresponding change in kotlin-native."
}